Bump Mapping
Motivation
  • Most surfaces not completely smooth
    • Could add lots of geometry
    • But that increases memory requirements & render time
  • Most visual impact is from surface irregularities interacting with light
    • We can perturb the normals to get apparent detail
    • Drawback: Won’t be visible along silhouette of object
Example
  • The geometry is totally smooth; only normal perturbed
  • Note that silhouettes do not show variations!
  • Link: https://www.ssucet.org/~jhudson/20/2802/webgl-bumpmap
Procedure
  • We could manipulate normals in VS/FS code
    • Very flexible
    • But not easy for artists to create
Bumpmap
  • Alternate approach: We use a texture to tell how to perturb normals
    • Easier for artists: Can create normal map at same time as rest of mesh
    • Standard plug-ins for Photoshop, etc.
Strategy
  • We’ll use the three color channels (rgb) to tell how to perturb the normal in 3D space
  • One scheme: Use red to tell x perturbation, green for y, blue for z
  • This isn’t good, however
Problem
  • Imagine we have some brick walls and we want to apply a bumpmap to them
Problem
  • We’d like to use the same bumpmap for all the walls
  • But: Notice that the xyz perturbation direction is different for each wall
    • On one wall, we might want to tweak the x direction
    • But on the other wall, we’d need to tweak z instead
  • We could make separate bumpmaps for each wall…
    • …But that gets tedious
Problem
  • Even worse, what if we want to apply a bumpmap to a sphere?
    • Every face would need a different mapping
      • Due to continuous curvature
  • We need a better approach
TBN
  • We’ll use TBN (Tangent-Bitangent-Normal) coordinates instead
  • Imagine we put a “mini coordinate system” at each vertex
    • Blue arrow is unperturbed normal (call it “N”)
    • Red arrow: “Tangent vector” (T)
    • Green arrow: “Bitangent vector” (B)
TBN
  • We’ll interpret the bumpmap texture as giving the normal perturbation in TBN space
  • Perturbed normal = v1T + v2B + v3N for some values v
    • -1 ≤ v1, v2, v3 ≤ 1
Bumpmap
  • We get the v1, v2, v3 from the bumpmap texture
    • Textures give us values from 0…1
    • We need perturbation values from -1…1
  • So we remap: 2.0 * (textureColor.rgb - vec3(0.5))
  • v1 comes from red, v2 from green, v3 from blue
Example
  • Totally unperturbed normal: v1=0, v2=0, v3=1
  • Perturbed normal = 0T+0B+1N=N
  • So an “identity” bumpmap would have color (0.5,0.5,1.0)
    • Most normal maps leave majority of normal vectors alone (or “almost alone”)
    • So they predominently have “periwinkle” color
Example
  • Here’s a normal map for a brick wall
Example
  • A normal map for a brick wall with irregular bricks
Example
  • A bump map for a coin
Question
  • How do we know which parts of 3D object map to which parts of normal map?
  • Often we use ordinary texture coordinates to establish correspondance
  • There’s no reason we couldn’t use a separate set of texture coordinates, though
TBN
  • Now we can determine what the tangent and bitangent directions should be at each vertex
  • Suppose we move across texture, from left to right
    • This will correspond to moving across object surface in some direction
    • We’ll define this as the tangent direction
  • Suppose we move across texture from bottom to top
    • This will correspond to moving across object surface in some other direction
    • We’ll define this as the bitangent direction
Compute
  • GLTF files already contain tangent information
  • See appendix for details on how to compute it ourselves…
Setup
  • VS has another vertex attribute: Tangent
  • This means Mesh needs to setup vertex puller slot
    • 0=Position
    • 1=Texture coordinate
    • 2=Normal
    • 3=Tangent (New!)
  • Often, bumpmaps use different texture coordinates than color textures
    • 4=Bumpmap texture coordinates (New!)
Draw
  • FS has additional texture: Bumpmap texture
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray baseTexture;
layout(binding=1) uniform sampler2DArray emissionTexture;
layout(binding=3) uniform sampler2DArray bumpmapTexture;
  • Why 3? We’ll use binding 2 for something else…
  • Mesh draw needs to set the bumpmap texture
VS
  • Change VS: Takes additional input:
layout(location=3) in vec3 tangent;
  • VS sends tangent to FS unchanged
  • Change VS: Don’t multiply normal with worldMatrix
    • Send it through unchanged to FS
FS
  • FS is where the real work goes on
  • We have these inputs:
    • Object space normal N
    • Object space tangent T
  • First, compute object space bitangent using Gram-Schmidt process
Gram-Schmidt
  • Normalize N
  • Compute: T=T-(T ⋅ N)N
  • Normalize T
  • Compute B using either:
    • B=B-(N ⋅ B)N-(T ⋅ B)T
    • B=N × T
  • Normalize B
FS
  • Next, sample color from bumpmap texture
    • Something like this:
    • tmp = texture( bumpmapTexture, vec3(v_texcoord,0.0) );
  • Remap: 0…1 → -1…1
    • This gives us tangent space (TBN) normal β
    • Let T=object space tangent, B=object space bitangent, N=object space normal
      • We got T and N from the VS; we computed B in the shader
  • Goal: Compute: N’=perturbed normal in object space
FS
N’ = [ βx βy βz ]⎡⎢⎢⎢⎣ Tx Ty Tz       Bx By Bz       Nx Ny Nz ⎤⎥⎥⎥⎦
FS
  • Pitfall: GLSL’s mat3() takes parameters in column major order!
FS
  • Multiply N’ by worldMatrix
  • Then do lighting computations as usual
Screenie
  • Random screenshot: The wall and floor are smooth geometrically
Assignment
  • Implement bumpmapping
    • Note that the dungeon uses texture coordinate set 2 for the bumpmaps
Appendix
  • Computing TBN vectors
Definitions
  • q0 ,q1 ,q2 = Triangle vertices in object space.
  • p = some point inside the triangle, in object space
  • s,t = texture coordinates at p
  • T0T1T2= tangent vectors for q0 ,q1 ,q2
  • B0,B1,B2= bitangent vectors for q0 ,q1 ,q2
  • s0,s1,s2= s texture coordinates at q0 ,q1 ,q2
  • t0,t1,t2= t texture coordinates at q0 ,q1 ,q2
Math
  • Want to choose T and B so that this is always true:
    qi = q  : sub : +(s_{i}-s0)T+(t_{i}-t0)B` * Idea: If we start at q_{i} and move Δs units in the T direction and Δt units in the B direction, we end up at p * Where Δs and Δt are the changes in s and t, respectively, from qi to p
  • Looks like we just need to do some algebra!
Math
  • We will have a simpler notation if we measure everything with respect to q0
  • So:
    • q’i = qi − q0
    • s’i = si − s0
    • t’i = ti − t0
    • p’ = p − q0
  • This tweaks the equation from the previous slide a bit:
    • q’i = (s’i)T + (t’i)B
    • Because s’0 = 0, t’0 = 0, q’0 = 0
Math
  • We want:
    • s’0T + t’0B = q’0
    • s’1T + t’1B = q’1
    • s’2T + t’2B = q’2
Math
  • s’0T + t’0B = q’0
    • 0T+0B=0 (trivial!)
  • The other two are vector equations, so they have x, y, and z components
Math
  • s’1Tx + t’1Bx = q’1x
  • s’1Ty + t’1By = q’1y
  • s’1Tz + t’1Bz = q’1z
  • s’2Tx + t’2Bx = q’1x
  • s’2Ty + t’2By = q’2y
  • s’2Tz + t’2Bz = q’2z
Rewrite
  • We can rewrite those six equations as one matrix operation:
⎡⎢⎣ s’1 t’1     s’2 t’2 ⎤⎥⎦⎡⎢⎣ Tx Ty Tz       Bx By Bz ⎤⎥⎦ = ⎡⎢⎣ q’1x q’1y q’1z       q’2x q’2y q’2z ⎤⎥⎦
  • Exercise: Verify the six equations from the previous slide match this equation
Math
R = ⎡⎢⎣ s’1 t’1     s’2 t’2 ⎤⎥⎦
  • Claim:
R − 1 = (1)/(s’1t’2 − s’2t’1)⎡⎢⎣ t’2  − t’1      − s’2 s’1 ⎤⎥⎦
  • Proof: Exercise for the reader…
Math
  • Multiply both sides of the equation by R − 1:
⎡⎢⎣ Tx Ty Tz       Bx By Bz ⎤⎥⎦ = R − 1⎡⎢⎣ q’1x q’1y q’1z       q’2x q’2y q’2z ⎤⎥⎦
Math
⎡⎢⎣ Tx Ty Tz       Bx By Bz ⎤⎥⎦ = (1)/(s’1t’2 − s’2t’1)⎡⎢⎣ t’2  − t’1      − s’2 s’1 ⎤⎥⎦⎡⎢⎣ q’1x q’1y q’1z       q’2x q’2y q’2z ⎤⎥⎦
  • Read out components of T and B
Math
  • Rare for T and B to be exactly orthogonal
  • Need to orthonormalize them
  • Use Gram-Schmidt process:
    • Normalize N
    • Compute: T=T-(T ⋅ N)N
    • Normalize T
    • Compute B using either:
      • B=B-(N ⋅ B)N-(T ⋅ B)T
      • B=N × T
    • Normalize B
Math
  • Could compute T,B for each triangle in isolation
  • Result: Discontinuities when moving from one triangle to another
  • So: If several triangles share a common vertex v:
    • Determine what each triangle thinks tangent should be for v
    • Average them all together
  • Note: We don’t store bitangents: We compute them as-needed when we render
    • So we wouldn’t need to even compute them at this point!
